msgid "Introduction"
msgstr ""

msgid "This book provides an introduction to creating and nurturing communities of contributors. This is a core part of Red Hat's mission, as manifested in the many communities where Red Hat is an active contributor."
msgstr ""

msgid "Red Hat employs contributors who work directly in upstream development on all parts of the open source architecture stack, from the Linux kernel to the thinnest skin of Ajax4Jsf. How these people interact with their communities is the first part of how Red Hat influences the growth of community."
msgstr ""

msgid "The qualities of the interaction of each individual contributor are as different as any human-to-human interaction. Over the course of time, these many interactions distill to a set of guiding principles that help us with the community growth and nurturing."
msgstr ""

msgid "Red Hat has collective community wisdom."
msgstr ""

msgid "We also have particular skill and luck in being thought and action leaders in many open communities. It has all been done in an open, ad hoc fashion, and it hasn't been written down before."
msgstr ""

msgid "So this book is a capturing of that distilled knowledge. It is also an active document, as that knowledge grows and changes, so do the contents of this book."
msgstr ""

msgid "This book is small and written on a wiki to facilitate collaboration and growth. If you have ideas to improve the <citetitle>The Open Source Way</citetitle>, you are encouraged to just start writing it down. Use a page's \"discussion\" tab to access the talk page."
msgstr ""

msgid "What this book is"
msgstr ""

msgid "A book that:"
msgstr ""

msgid "... describes a principle"
msgstr ""

msgid "... explains how to implement it"
msgstr ""

msgid "... and gives real world examples."
msgstr ""

msgid "A thin reference guide to richer, thicker works that explain Big Principles in Lots of Fancy Words."
msgstr ""

msgid "An open how-to manual, initially authored by the Red Hat <ulink url=\"http://fedoraproject.org/wiki/Community_Architecture\"> Community Architecture</ulink> team."
msgstr ""

msgid "Useful for much more than just code -- art/design, documentation, marketing, translation, IT, and so on"
msgstr ""

msgid "What it is not"
msgstr ""

msgid "Comprehensive for the sake of inclusion."
msgstr ""

msgid "We are focused on slim and useful."
msgstr ""

msgid "Overly repetitive of content already said and available elsewhere as free and open."
msgstr ""

msgid "Build on the work of others via the power of reference."
msgstr ""

msgid "Boring."
msgstr ""

msgid "What it is influenced by"
msgstr ""

msgid "There are some very comprehensive, thorough, and useful works, such as:"
msgstr ""

msgid "<citetitle><ulink url=\"http://producingoss.com/en/index.html\">Producing Open Source Software</ulink></citetitle>"
msgstr ""

msgid "<citetitle><ulink url=\"http://www.ewenger.com/pub/pubcultivatingbook.htm\"> Cultivating Communities of Practice</ulink></citetitle>."
msgstr ""

msgid "More influencers and good reads are found in <xref linkend=\"The_Open_Source_Way-Books_you_should_read\" /> and <xref linkend=\"The_Open_Source_Way-Data_and_references\" />."
msgstr ""

msgid "Essential terminology or 'Read this even if you think you know what it means'"
msgstr ""

msgid "This section is growing ..."
msgstr ""

msgid "This section is growing for a while as the <citetitle>The Open Source Way</citetitle> is written and terms need defining."
msgstr ""

msgid "Community"
msgstr ""

msgid "When people talk about community, they may be talking about very different things:"
msgstr ""

msgid "People who <emphasis role=\"italics\">use</emphasis> something"
msgstr ""

msgid "People who <emphasis role=\"italics\">like</emphasis> something"
msgstr ""

msgid "People who <emphasis role=\"italics\">advocate</emphasis> for a technology"
msgstr ""

msgid "People who <emphasis role=\"italics\">enable others</emphasis> to use something"
msgstr ""

msgid "People who <emphasis role=\"italics\">contribute to improve</emphasis> something"
msgstr ""

msgid "... and so on."
msgstr ""

msgid "When we talk about community in the <citetitle>The Open Source Way</citetitle>, we mean the community of contributors who are a superset to all other communities. The ones who, by getting things done, make it possible for many, many more to get much, much more done."
msgstr ""

msgid "This is the group of people who form intentionally and spontaneously around something important to them. It includes the people who use or benefit from the project, those who participate and share the project to wider audiences, and the contributors who are essential to growth and survival."
msgstr ""

msgid "Contributors are the oxygen. Without it, the animal chokes and dies."
msgstr ""

msgid "The community that contributes to improve something ..."
msgstr ""

msgid "The community that contributes to improve something is the one that defines the technology and the next generation of users, advocates, and enablers."
msgstr ""

msgid "Tactics"
msgstr ""

msgid "This is derived from military terminology. The common example is a group of soldiers who work with a squad leader to take and secure a hill."
msgstr ""

msgid "<firstterm>Tactics</firstterm> are the ideas, plans, methods, and means used to accomplish a goal. That is, tactics are the maneuvers used to achieve an objective that is set by strategy."
msgstr ""

msgid "In Fedora, the strict yet clever <ulink url=\"http://fedoraproject.org/wiki/Packaging\">packaging guidelines</ulink> are a strong-arm tactic that enforces the Fedora strategy of good packaging of only free and open source software."
msgstr ""

msgid "Strategy"
msgstr ""

msgid "<firstterm>Strategy</firstterm> focuses on everything from which hill to secure, to deciding which miltary campaigns to engage in."
msgstr ""

msgid "A term from military science, strategy is the focus of the command group. Strategy focuses on setting goals and which groups can obtain the goals."
msgstr ""

msgid "Once the \"who, what, where, when, and why\" is decided, tactics takes over as the \"how\"."
msgstr ""

msgid "The Fedora strategy of creating and supporting only FLOSS is derived from the culture of the community combined with a pragmatic view of the legal and business landscape."
msgstr ""

msgid "Planets and blogs"
msgstr ""

msgid "A <ulink url=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog\">blog</ulink> is a mix of personal and project writing that comes from a participant or contributor."
msgstr ""

msgid "The idea of a <firstterm>blog planet</firstterm> is to show the width and depth of personalities in a community, and what they are doing."
msgstr ""

msgid "It intentionally allows for personal expression. In other words, the content is not all community specific. It is sometimes wildly off topic."
msgstr ""

msgid "The <ulink url=\"http://planet.fedoraproject.org\">Fedora Planet</ulink> is a good example, with blogs aggregated from willing contributors. People add themselves to the planet, and it is a mix of languages, topics, skill levels, and project interest. All aspects of the Fedora Project are covered there on a daily basis, with a wide variety of contributors from Packaging, Art and Design, Marketing, upstream development, and so on."
msgstr ""

msgid "Leaderless organizations"
msgstr ""

msgid "A leaderless organization is <firstterm>decentralized</firstterm>, meaning it does not rely upon a central authority for leadership, strategy, or tactics. Being decentralized makes it easier to heal, faster to respond and innovate, and more able to grow in scale."
msgstr ""

msgid "An example of a large leaderless organization is the Internet. Not just the set of agreements that makes the structure work, but all the way down to the wire protocols that route around damage in the network, such as when a backhoe slices through a fiber link between two ISPs."
msgstr ""

msgid "In projects, <ulink url=\"http://wikipedia.org\">Wikipedia</ulink> is a decentralized organization, while the <ulink url=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Encyclop%C3%A6dia_Britannica\"> Encyclopaedia Brittanica</ulink> is a classic centralized organization."
msgstr ""

msgid "The idea of the leaderless organization is put forth in the book <ulink url=\"http://www.starfishandspider.com/\">The Starfish and The Spider</ulink>."
msgstr ""

msgid "Version control"
msgstr ""

msgid "Version control is the comfortable insurance that means you can sleep soundly at night."
msgstr ""

msgid "A <firstterm>version control system (VCS)</firstterm> keeps track of the differences in versions of content. Properly implemented, it is nearly disaster proof."
msgstr ""

msgid "When a document is saved in to a VCS, the difference between the current saved copy and the one just before it is stored. The same occurred at all previous saves. This makes it possible to restore a document to any point in its save history. It is also possible to return to a previous save point and start a new pathway of saves from there. In code this is called <firstterm>branching</firstterm>, with the original code in the central <firstterm>trunk</firstterm>."
msgstr ""

msgid "When you work with a web-based tool to write, edit, and display a document, you are using version control. All content management systems and wikis use a form of version control to capture and display the differences between edits."
msgstr ""

msgid "Version control provides noisy reporting. Anyone who is interested or able may watch the stream of changes, or derive reports from them. Watching and commenting on version saves as they occur is a hallmark of the open source methodology."
msgstr ""

msgid "Content v. code repositories"
msgstr ""

msgid "Code is a specialized form of content. There are many similarities between repositories of code and content. The major difference is in the tools."
msgstr ""

msgid "Code repository tools focus on centralized or decentralized development of the code. The ability to return to a point in time and branch from there is essential."
msgstr ""

msgid "Content repository tools also include the ability to return to previous points in a documents save history. They also include management tools, such as team automation in MediaWiki, and workflow, publishing, and lifecycle components in a content management system (CMS)."
msgstr ""

